The actual set that makes text readable in different background colors using mix-blend-mode is:

color: rgba(255,150,200,1);
mix-blend-mode: exclusion; 

The color property sets the color of the text to a highly contrasting color that will stand out against almost any background color. The mix-blend-mode property then uses the exclusion blending mode to ensure that the text remains legible even when placed on a colorful or complex background. The exclusion blending mode effectively subtracts the text color from the background color to create a new, contrasted color that is easier to read.

If you want the text to remain green while using mix-blend-mode, you can simply set the color property to green. The mix-blend-mode property will then blend the green color with the background color according to the selected blending mode (in this case, exclusion), while still maintaining the green base color of the text.

Here is an example CSS code for achieving this:

```
.background-text-container {
  position: relative;
  top: 50%;
  left: 49%;
  transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
  max-width: 90%;
  max-height: 90%;
  white-space: nowrap;
  text-align: center;
  background-color: rgba(55, 255, 55, 0);
  color: green;
  mix-blend-mode: exclusion;
}
```

In this code snippet, the color property is set to green to achieve the desired text color, and the mix-blend-mode property is set to exclusion to blend the green text color with the background color using the exclusion blending mode. This should achieve the effect you are looking for.

