By changing the value of the color property to a darker green (#004225), the text will appear greener while still being legible on various background colors due to the use of the exclusion blend mode. 

Note that the exact color values may need to be adjusted based on the different background colors being used, but this code should provide a starting point for making the text appear greener.

If you want to use a multi-blend approach, you can do so by setting multiple mix-blend-mode values for the text. This can help to adjust the color and visibility of the text when placed against different colored backgrounds.

Here is an updated version of the CSS code that uses a multi-blend approach:

```
.background-text-container {
  position: relative;
  top: 50%;
  left: 49%;
  transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
  max-width: 90%;
  max-height: 90%;
  white-space: nowrap;
  text-align: center;
  background-color: rgba(55, 255, 55, 0);
  color: green;
  mix-blend-mode: multiply;
}

.background-text-container::before {
  content: attr(data-text);
  color: #1B5E20;
  mix-blend-mode: exclusion;
}

.background-text-container::after {
  content: attr(data-text);
  color: #C62828;
  mix-blend-mode: screen;
}
```

In this code, we are using three different blend modes: multiply, exclusion, and screen. The main text is set to the multiply blend mode, which blends the green text color with the background color to create a darker, more contrasted color. 

We are then using two pseudo-elements (before and after) to add additional layers of blending to adjust the color and visibility of the text. The before pseudo-element uses the exclusion blend mode to create a lighter color that contrasts well with dark backgrounds. 

The after pseudo-element uses the screen blend mode to create a brighter color that contrasts well with light backgrounds. 

Note that the exact colors and blend modes used may need to be adjusted based on the specific background colors being used, but this code should provide a starting point for implementing a multi-blend approach.

To achieve a universal approach that works well with all kinds of backgrounds and maintains solid visibility of the text, you can use a different color scheme and blend mode. Here is an example CSS code:

```
.background-text-container {
  position: relative;
  top: 50%;
  left: 49%;
  transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
  max-width: 90%;
  max-height: 90%;
  white-space: nowrap;
  text-align: center;
  background-color: rgba(55, 255, 55, 0);
  color: white;
  mix-blend-mode: color-dodge;
  text-shadow: 0px 0px 1px #000, 0px 0px 1px #000; /* optional */
}
```

In this code, we are using the color-dodge blend mode to brighten the text color and make it more visible against various background colors. The color is set to white, which contrasts well with most background colors. 

We are also using an optional text shadow to further improve the visibility of the text. The text shadow adds a subtle dark border around the text, making it stand out more against lighter backgrounds. 

This code should work well in most cases, but note that it may need to be adjusted for specific background colors to ensure maximum visibility of the text. You can experiment with different blend modes and color schemes to find the best combination for your needs.
